Take a sad song and make it better


Background

In a previous analsys, I tested whether more positive or happy Ramones songs tend to be more popular, and found that there did seem to be a correlation such that the positive the song, the more popular it tended to be.

I thought I would compare it against The Beatles to see if the same type of correlation holds true. I would like to see if valence has a meaningful relationship to popularity for the Beatles and the Ramones, and whether or not that relationship differs significantly between the two.

I will again be using analytics from Spotify because it’s widely used and should provide a reasonably reliable measure of popularity. I will be also be using an attribute that Spotify terms “valence” as “the musical positiveness conveyed”. Put another way, it measures how happy a song is. Both popularity and valence are rated by Spotify on a scale of 1 to 10.

I used the Spotify API to gather audio analytics about every Ramones song on each of their 14 studio albums, as well as the 13 studio albums by the Beatles.

Hypothesis

We want to check if there there is a significant change in slope when comparing the Beatles against the Ramones. We’ll assume that there is no difference until there is sufficient evidence to convince us otherwise.

\[ H_0 : \beta_3 = 0 \] \[ H_a : \beta_3 \not= 0 \]

I opted not to include a test for the popularity when valence is zero, because it’s reasonable to accept as common knowledge that The Beatles were vastly more popular the Ramones, and such a test wouldn’t be very interesting. What’s more interesting is the relationship of the slope, and whether the popularity of a song can be predicted using the same model across multiple artists.

Model (click to view)

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_{\text{Popularity}} = \overbrace{\overbrace{\beta_0}^{\text{Y-int.}} + \underbrace{\beta_1}_{\text{Slope}} \overbrace{X_{i1}}^{\text{Valence}}}^{\text{Ramones}} + \overbrace{\underbrace{\beta_2}_{\text{Y-int. change}} \overbrace{X_{i2}}^{\text{1 if Beatles}} + \underbrace{\beta_3}_{\text{change in slope}} \overbrace{X_{i1} X_{i2}}^{\text{Interaction}}}^{\text{The Beatles}} + \epsilon_i \]

The two bands in this case are going to be the explanatory variables, so for modeling the Ramones, \(X_{i2}\) would be zero giving us the model \(Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i2} + \epsilon_i\) after canceling out \(\beta_2\) and \(\beta_3\).

For modeling the Beatles, \(X_{i2}\) equals 1 which gives us the model \(Y_i = (\beta_0 + \beta_2) + (\beta_1 + \beta_3) X_{i2} + \epsilon_i\). The goal of this model is to determine the change in the y intercept from the earlier base (Ramones) hence \((\beta_0 + \beta_2)\). The change in slope is shown in the model as \((\beta_1 + \beta_3)\).

\(\alpha = 0.05\) 
bandslm <- lm(pop ~ valence + artist + valence:artist, data=bands)

pander(bandslm)
Fitting linear model: pop ~ valence + artist + valence:artist
  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 13.26 2.281 5.815 1.461e-08
valence 0.1373 0.03253 4.221 3.165e-05
artistThe Beatles 46.22 2.997 15.42 1.485e-40
valence:artistThe Beatles -0.1824 0.04325 -4.217 3.217e-05

The second row shows the \(\beta_1\) coefficient which means the Ramones have a slope of .1373, meaning that for every one point increase of valence in a Ramones song, we should see on average a .1373 increase in popularity.

The fourth row (valence:artistThe Beatles) indicates the difference in the slope of The Beatles regression line from the Ramones (\(\beta_3\)), and the negative value indicates the Beatles have less steep of a slope.

theme_bw()

Interpretation

With a p-value of 3.217e-05, this is sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a signficant difference between the two slopes. My interpretation of this is that Beatles songs don’t benefit as much as Ramones songs from having a positive vibe. It’s hard to say why this is, but some possibilities could be that The Beatles are more skilled at writing more somber music, or there could be a correlation with people who are generally interested in a particular genre and what type of songs they prefer. It could also have to do with time period, given the Ramones originated in the United States in the late 1970’s, and the Beatles started in the UK in the early 1960’s.

Caveats

There are a couple things to keep in mind about the results of this data. First, the attributes sampled were from one music medium out of many, and it’s always possible that the data is derived from an disproportionate amount of young hip techno-wizards, leaving out Uncle Bob and Hipster Mac who listen to vinyl records. We also don’t know the specifics of how Spotify measure popularity or valence.

In regards to the appropriateness check it looks like we have a bit of skew in the data, looking at the Q-Q plot. The vertical line in the Residuals Vs Fitted plot is showing there is appropriate constant variance, but it’s showing a multi-linear trend.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(bandslm, which=1)
qqPlot(bandslm$residuals,
 ylab = "Standardised Residuals",
 xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles")
title("Normal Q-Q", line = .5,
 cex.main = 1.5, font.main = 1)
plot(bandslm$residuals,
 ylab = "Residuals")
title("Residuals vs Order", line = .5,
 cex.main = 1.5, font.main = 1)
